    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "i'm looking at my student loan statement and the principal isn't going down as fast as i thought it would. i'm making my full payments every month but it feels like nothing is happening. can u explain how the interest is actually calculated each month and why it feels like the balance barely moves at first?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, the slow-moving principal on your student loan is a common feeling, but don't worry, it's all part of the loan's magic. When you make your full payments, you're essentially paying the interest first, which is like the loan's way of saying, \"Hey, I need my share of the treasure.\" The principal, or the actual amount you borrowed, only starts to decrease after you've paid off this interest. It's like you're giving the loan a little bit of your treasure each month, but the loan is holding onto a good chunk of it until the interest is fully paid off. So, while it may feel like nothing is happening, you're actually slowly chipping away at the interest, and once that's done, you'll see the principal decrease more noticeably. Keep at it, and soon you'll be seeing the principal drop faster, like a sneaky goblin finally getting caught after a long chase.",
